The relational database service overview.

The relational database service runs the database engine on instances behind the scenes, with block storage underneath, and exposes a connection endpoint, a maintenance window, and a small set of configuration knobs. Everything else, patching the operating system, upgrading the engine, replacing failed hardware, taking backups, setting up replicas, and flipping to a standby on failure, is AWS's job. You don't get a shell; there's no operating-system access, and the cost of that lockdown is that any feature AWS hasn't certified, a custom extension or a kernel-level agent, isn't reachable.

It supports six engines: MySQL, Postgres, MariaDB, Oracle, Microsoft sequel server, and Db2, all sharing the same managed plane of backups, replicas, and monitoring. The right reason to run a database on a raw instance instead is a feature the service doesn't expose; for everything else, the managed service wins once you count the cost of operations.

Underneath, it sits on block storage with autoscaling that grows the volume automatically as free space falls, which is the right default for any workload whose growth isn't perfectly predictable.
